PURPORTArjuna was addressed as the \xc3\x92son of P\xe2\x80\x9eth\xe2\x88\x92,\xc3\x93 who happened to be the sister of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa\xc3\x95s father Vasudeva. Therefore Arjuna had a blood relationship with K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. If the son of a ksatriya declines to fight, he is a k\xc5\x92atriya in name only, and if the son of a br\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9aa acts impiously, he is a br\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9aa in name only. \nSuch k\xc5\x92atriyas and br\xe2\x88\x92hma\xe2\x80\x9aas are unworthy sons of their fathers; therefore, K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa did not want Arjuna to become an unworthy son of a k\xc5\x92atriya. Arjuna was the most intimate friend of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, and K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa was directly guiding him on \nthe chariot; but in spite of all these credits, if Arjuna abandoned the battle, he would be committing an infamous act; therefore K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa said that such an attitude in Arjuna did not fit his personality. Arjuna might argue that he would give up the battle on the grounds of his magnanimous attitude for the \nmost respectable Bh\xe2\x80\x9d\xc5\x92ma and his relatives, but K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa considered that sort of magnanimity not approved by authority. Therefore, such magnanimity or so-called nonviolence should be given up by persons like Arjuna under the direct guidance of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa.
