PURPORTAccording to the Nirukti, or the Vedic dictionary, sa\xef\xac\x81khya means that which describes phenomena in detail, and sa\xef\xac\x81khya refers to that philosophy which describes the real nature of the soul. And yoga involves controlling the \nsenses. Arjuna\xc3\x95s proposal not to fight was based on sense gratification. '
b'Forgetting his prime duty, he wanted to cease fighting because he thought that by not killing his relatives and kinsmen he would be happier than by enjoying the kingdom by conquering his cousins and brothers, the sons of Dh\xe2\x80\x9etar\xe2\x88\x92\xc5\x92\xc4\xb1ra. In both ways, the basic principles were for sense gratification. Happiness derived from conquering them and happiness derived by seeing kinsmen alive are both on the basis of persona1 sense gratification, for there is a sacrifice of wisdom and duty. K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, therefore, wanted to explain to Arjuna that by killing the body of his grandfather he would not be killing the soul proper, and He \nexplained that all individual persons, including the Lord Himself, are eternal individuals; they were individuals in the past, they are individuals in the present, and they will continue to remain individuals in the future, because all of us are individual souls eternally, and we simply change our bodily dress in different manners. But, actually, we keep our individuality even after liberation from the bondage of material dress. An analytical study of the soul and the body has been very graphically explained by Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. And this \ndescriptive knowledge of the soul and the body from different angles of vision has been described here as s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya, in terms of the Nirukti dictionary. This s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya has nothing to do with the s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya philosophy of the atheist Kapila. Long before the imposter Kapila\xc3\x95s s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya, the s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya philosophy was expounded in the \xe2\x80\xa1r\xe2\x80\x9dmad-Bh\xe2\x88\x92gavatam by the true Lord Kapila, the incarnation explained by Him that the Puru\xc5\x92a, or the Supreme Lord, is active and that He \ncreates by looking over the prak\xe2\x80\x9eti. This is accepted in the Vedas and in the G\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92. The description in the Vedas indicates that the Lord glanced over the prak\xe2\x80\x9eti, or nature, and impregnated it with atomic individuals souls. All these individuals are working in the material world for sense gratification, and under the spell of material energy they are thinking of being enjoyers. This mentality is dragged to the last point of liberation when the living entity wants to become one with the Lord. This is the last snare of m\xe2\x88\x92y\xe2\x88\x92 or sense gratificatory illusion, and it is only after many, many births of such sense gratificatory activities that a great soul surrenders unto V\xe2\x88\x92sudeva, Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, thereby fulfilling the search after the ultimate truth.Arjuna has already accepted K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa as his spiritual master by surrendering himself unto Him: \xe2\x80\x9ci\xc5\x92yas te \xc3\x95ha\xe2\x80\xb9 \xe2\x80\x9c\xe2\x88\x92dhi m\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\xb9 tv\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\xb9 prapannam. Consequently, K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa will now tell him about the working process in buddhi-yoga, or karma-yoga, or in other words, the practice of devotional service only for the sense '
b'gratification of the Lord. This buddhi-yoga is clearly explained in Chapter Ten, verse ten, as being direct communion with the Lord, who is sitting as Param\xe2\x88\x92tm\xe2\x88\x92 in everyone\xc3\x95s heart. But such communion does not take place without devotional service. One who is therefore situated in devotional or transcendental loving service to the Lord, or, in other words, in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness, attains to this stage of buddhi-yoga by the special grace of the Lord. The Lord says, therefore, that only to those who are always engaged in devotional service out of transcendental love does He award the pure \nknowledge of devotion in love. In that way the devotee can reach Him easily in the ever-blissful kingdom of God.Thus the buddhi-yoga mentioned in this verse is the devotional service of the Lord, and the word s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya mentioned herein has nothing to do with the atheistic s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya-yoga enunciated by the impostor Kapila. One should not, therefore, misunderstand that the s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya-yoga mentioned herein has any connection with the atheistic s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya. Nor did that philosophy have any \ninfluence during that time; nor would Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa care to mention such godless philosophical speculations. Real s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya philosophy is described by Lord Kapila in the \xe2\x80\xa1r\xe2\x80\x9dmad-Bh\xe2\x88\x92gavatam, but even that s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya has nothing to do with the current topics. Here, s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya means analytical description of the body and the soul. Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa made an analytical description of the soul just to bring Arjuna to the point of buddhi-yoga, or bhakti-yoga. Therefore, Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa\xc3\x95s s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya and Lord Kapila\xc3\x95s s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya, as described in the Bh\xe2\x88\x92gavatam; \nare one and the same. They are all bhakti-yoga. He said, therefore, that only the less intelligent class of men make a distinction between s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya-yoga and bhakti-yoga.\nOf course, atheistic s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya-yoga has nothing to do with bhakti-yoga, yet the unintelligent claim that the atheistic s\xe2\x88\x92\xef\xac\x81khya-yoga is referred to in the Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92.One should therefore understand that buddhi-yoga means to work in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa \nconsciousness, in the full bliss and knowledge of devotional service. One who works for the satisfaction of the Lord only, however difficult such work may be, is working under the principles of buddhi-yoga and finds himself always in transcendental bliss. By such transcendental engagement, one achieves all transcendental qualities automatically, by the grace of the Lord, and thus his liberation is complete in itself, without his making extraneous endeavors to acquire knowledge. There is much difference between work in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa '
b'consciousness and work for fruitive results, especially in the matter of sense gratification for achieving results in terms of family or material happiness. Buddhi-yoga is therefore the transcendental quality of the work that we perform.
