Arjuna said: What are the symptoms of one whose consciousness is thus merged in Transcendence? How does he speak, and what is his language? How does he \nsit, and how does he walk?
PURPORTAs there are symptoms for each and every man, in terms of his particular situation, similarly one who is K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious has his particular nature\xc3\x91talking, walking, thinking, feeling, etc. As a rich man has his symptoms by \nwhich he is known as a rich man, as a diseased man has his symptoms, by which he is known as diseased, or as a learned man has his symptoms, so a man in transcendental consciousness of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa has specific symptoms in various dealings. One can know his specific symptoms from the Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92. Most important is how the man in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness speaks, for speech is the most important quality of any man. It is said that a fool is undiscovered as long as he does not speak, and certainly a well-dressed fool cannot be identified \nunless he speaks, but as soon as he speaks, he reveals himself at once. The immediate symptom of a K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious man is that he speaks only of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa and of matters relating to Him. Other symptoms then automatically follow, as stated below.'
