One who knows the transcendental nature of My appearance and activities does not, upon leaving the body, take his birth again in this material world, but attains My eternal abode, O Arjuna.
PURPORTThe Lord\xc3\x95s descent from His transcendental abode is already explained in the 6th verse. One who can understand the truth of the appearance of the Personality of Godhead is already liberated from material bondage, and therefore he returns to the kingdom of God immediately after quitting this present material body. Such liberation of the living entity from material bondage is not at all easy. The impersonalists and the yog\xe2\x80\x9ds attain liberation only after much trouble and many, many births. Even then, the liberation they achieve\xc3\x91merging into the impersonal brahmajyoti of the Lord\xc3\x91is only \npartial, and there is the risk of returning again to this material world. But the devotee, simply by understanding the transcendental nature of the body and activities of the Lord, attains the abode of the Lord after ending this body and does not run the risk of returning again to this material world. In the Brahma-sa\xe2\x80\xb9hit\xe2\x88\x92 it is stated that the Lord has many, many forms and incarnations: '
b'Although there are many transcendental forms of the Lord, they are still one and the same Supreme Personality of Godhead. One has to understand this fact with conviction, although it is incomprehensible to mundane scholars and empiric philosophers. As stated in the Vedas:eko devo nitya-l\xe2\x80\x9dl\xe2\x88\x92nurakto bhakta-vy\xe2\x88\x92p\xe2\x80\x9d h\xe2\x80\x9edy antar\xe2\x88\x92tm\xe2\x88\x92."The one Supreme Personality of Godhead is eternally engaged in many, many transcendental forms in relationships with His unalloyed devotees." This \nVedic version is confirmed in this verse of the G\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 personally by the Lord. He who accepts this truth on the strength of the authority of the Vedas and of the Supreme Personality of Godhead and who does not waste time in \nphilosophical speculations attains the highest perfectional stage of liberation. Simply by accepting this truth on faith, one can, without a doubt, attain liberation. The Vedic version, "tattvamasi," is actually applied in this case. \nAnyone who understands Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa to be the Supreme, or who says unto the Lord, "You are the same Supreme Brahman, the Personality of Godhead" is certainly liberated instantly, and consequently his entrance into the transcendental association of the Lord is guaranteed. In other words, such a faithful devotee of the Lord attains perfection, and this is confirmed by the following Vedic assertion:tam eva viditv\xe2\x88\x92tim\xe2\x80\x9etyumeti n\xe2\x88\x92nya\xc5\xa1 panth\xe2\x88\x92 vidyate ayan\xe2\x88\x92ya.One can attain the perfect stage of liberation from birth and death simply by knowing the Lord, the Supreme Personality of Godhead. There is no \nalternative because anyone who does not understand Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa as the Supreme Personality of Godhead is surely in the mode of ignorance. Consequently he will not attain salvation, simply, so to speak, by licking the outer surface of the bottle of honey, or by interpreting the Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 \naccording to mundane scholarship. Such empiric philosophers may assume very important roles in the material world, but they are not necessarily eligible for liberation. Such puffed up mundane scholars have to wait for the causeless mercy of the devotee of the Lord. One should therefore cultivate K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness with faith and knowledge, and in this way attain perfection.'
