b'considered to be a failure in life as long as he makes no inquiry about the nature of work for fruitive results, for as long as one is engrossed in the consciousness of sense gratification, one has to transmigrate from one body to another. Although the mind may be engrossed in fruitive activities and influenced by ignorance, one must develop a love for devotional service to V\xe2\x88\x92sudeva. Only then can one have the opportunity to get out of the bondage of material existence." (Bh\xe2\x88\x92g. 5.5.4-6)Therefore, j\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92na (or knowledge that one is not this material body but spirit soul) is not sufficient for liberation. One has to act in the status of spirit soul, \notherwise there is no escape from material bondage. Action in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is not, however, action on the fruitive platform. Activities performed in full knowledge strengthen one\xc3\x95s advancement in real knowledge. Without K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness, mere renunciation of fruitive activities does not actually purify the heart of a conditioned soul. As long as the heart is not purified, one has to work on the fruitive platform. But action in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa \nconsciousness automatically helps one escape the result of fruitive action so that one need not descend to the material platform. Therefore, action in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is always superior to renunciation, which always entails a risk of falling. Renunciation without K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is incomplete, as is Bhak ti-ras\xe2\x88\x92m\xe2\x80\x9eta-sindbu.pr\xe2\x88\x92pa\xc5\x81cikatay\xe2\x88\x92 buddhy\xe2\x88\x92 hari-sambandhi-vastuna\xc5\xa1mumuk\xc5\x92ubhi\xc5\xa1 parity\xe2\x88\x92go vair\xe2\x88\x92gya\xe2\x80\xb9 phalgu kathyate."Renunciation by persons eager to achieve liberation of things which are related to the Supreme Personality of Godhead, though they are material, is called incomplete renunciation." Renunciation is compete when it is in the knowledge that everything in existence belongs to the Lord and that no one should claim proprietorship over anything. One should understand that, factually, nothing belongs to anyone. Then where is the question of \nrenunciation? One who knows that everything is K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa\xc3\x95s property is always situated in renunciation. Since everything belongs to K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, everything should be employed in the service of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. This perfect form of action in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is far better than any amount of artificial renunciation by a sanny\xe2\x88\x92s\xe2\x80\x9d of the M\xe2\x88\x92y\xe2\x88\x92v\xe2\x88\x92d\xe2\x80\x9d school.'
