The sages, knowing Me as the ultimate purpose of all sacrifices and austerities, the Supreme Lord of all planets and demigods and the benefactor and well-wisher of all living entities, attain peace from the pangs of material miseries.
PURPORTThe conditioned souls within the clutches of illusory energy are all anxious to attain peace in the material world. But they do not know the formula for peace, which is explained in this part of the Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92. The greatest peace formula is simply this: Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa is the beneficiary in all human activities. Men should offer everything to the transcendental service of the Lord because He is the proprietor of all planets and the demigods thereon. No one is greater than He. He is greater than the greatest of the demigods, Lord \xe2\x80\xa1iva and Lord Brahm\xe2\x88\x92. In the Vedas the Supreme Lord is described as tam \xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x80\x9cvar\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\x9a\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\xb9 \nparama\xe2\x80\xb9 mahe\xe2\x80\x9cvaram. Under the spell of illusion, living entities are trying to be lords of all they survey, but actually they are dominated by the material energy of the Lord. The Lord is the master of material nature, and the conditioned souls are under the stringent rules of material nature. Unless one understands these bare facts, it is not possible to achieve peace in the world '
b'either individually or collectively. This is the sense of Kssna consciousness: Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa is the supreme predominator, and all living entities, including the great demigods, are His subordinates. One can attain perfect peace only in complete K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness.This Fifth Chapter is a practical explanation of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness, generally known as karma-yoga. The question of mental speculation as to how karma-yoga can give liberation is answered herewith. To work in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is to work with the complete knowledge of the Lord as the predominator. Such \nwork is not different from transcendental knowledge. Direct K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is bhakti-yoga, and j\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92na-yoga is a path leading to bhakti-yoga. K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness means to work in full knowledge of one\xc3\x95s relationship with the Supreme Absolute, and the perfection of this consciousness is full knowledge of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, or the Supreme Personality of Godhead. A pure soul is the eternal servant of God as His fragmental part and parcel. He comes into contact with m\xe2\x88\x92y\xe2\x88\x92 (illusion) due to the desire to lord it over m\xe2\x88\x92y\xe2\x88\x92, and that is \nthe cause of his many sufferings. As long as he is in contact with matter, he has to execute work in terms of material necessities. K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness, however, brings one into spiritual life even while one is within the jurisdiction of matter, for it is an arousing of spiritual existence by practice in the material world. The more one is advanced, the more he is freed from the clutches of matter. The Lord is not partial toward anyone. Everything depends on one\xc3\x95s practical performance of duties in an effort to control the senses and conquer \nthe influence of desire and anger. And, attaining K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness by controlling the above-mentioned passions, one remains factually in the transcendental stage, or brahman-nirv\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. The eightfold yoga mysticism is automatically practiced in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness because the ultimate purpose is served. There is gradual process of elevation in the practice of yama, niyama, \xe2\x88\x92sana, praty\xe2\x88\x92h\xe2\x88\x92ra, dhy\xe2\x88\x92na, dh\xe2\x88\x92ra\xe2\x80\x9a\xe2\x88\x92, pr\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\x9a\xe2\x88\x92y\xe2\x88\x92ma, and sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi. But these only \npreface perfection by devotional service, which alone can award peace to the \nhuman being. It is the highest perfection of life.Thus end the Bhaktivedanta Purports to the Fifth Chapter of the \xe2\x80\xa1r\xe2\x80\x9dmad-Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 in the matter of Karma-yoga, or Action in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa Consciousness.'
