A transcendentalist should always try to concentrate his mind on the Supreme Self; he should live alone in a secluded place and should always carefully control his mind. He should be free from desires and feelings of possessiveness.
PURPORTK\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa is realized in different degrees as Brahman, Param\xe2\x88\x92tm\xe2\x88\x92 and the Supreme Personality of Godhead. K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness means, concisely, to be always engaged in the transcendental loving service of the Lord. But those who are attached to the impersonal Brahman or the localized Supersoul are \nalso partially K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious, because impersonal Brahman is the spiritual ray of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa and Supersoul is the all-pervading partial expansion of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. Thus the impersonalist and the meditator are also indirectly K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious. A directly K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious person is the topmost transcendentalist because such a devotee knows what is meant by Brahman or Param\xe2\x88\x92tm\xe2\x88\x92. His knowledge of the Absolute Truth is perfect, whereas the impersonalist and the meditative yog\xe2\x80\x9d are imperfectly K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious.\nNevertheless, all of these are instructed herewith to be constantly engaged in their particular pursuits so that they may come to the highest perfection sooner or later. The first business of a transcendentalist is to keep the mind always on K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa. One should always think of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa and not forget Him even for a moment. Concentration of the mind on the Supreme is called sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi or trance. In order to concentrate the mind, one should always remain in \nseclusion and avoid disturbance by external objects. He should be very careful '
b'to accept favorable and reject unfavorable conditions that affect his realization. And, in perfect determination, he should not hanker after unnecessary material things that entangle him by feelings of possessiveness.All these perfections and precautions are perfectly executed when one is directly in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness because direct K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness means self-abnegation, wherein there is very little chance for material possessiveness. an\xe2\x88\x92saktasya vi\xc5\x92ay\xe2\x88\x92n yath\xe2\x88\x92rham upayu\xc5\x81jata\xc5\xa1nirbandha\xc5\xa1 k\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa-sambandhe yukta\xe2\x80\xb9 vair\xe2\x88\x92gyam ucyatepr\xe2\x88\x92pa\xc5\x81cikatay\xe2\x88\x92 buddhy\xe2\x88\x92 hari-sambandhi-vastuna\xc5\xa1mumuk\xc5\x92ubhi\xc5\xa1 parity\xe2\x88\x92go vair\xe2\x88\x92gya\xe2\x80\xb9 phalgu kathyate.(Bhakti-ras\xe2\x88\x92m\xe2\x80\x9eta-sindhu 2.255\xc3\x90256)"When one is not attached to anything, but at the same time accepts everything in relation to K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, one is rightly situated above possessiveness. On the other hand, one who rejects everything without knowledge of its relationship to K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa is not as complete in his renunciation."A K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious person well knows that everything belongs to K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, and thus he is always free from feelings of personal possession. As such, he has no \nhankering for anything on his own personal account. He knows how to accept things in favor of K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness and how to reject things unfavorable to K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness. He is always aloof from material things because he is always transcendental, and he is always alone, having nothing to do with persons not in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness. Therefore a person in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness is the perfect yog\xe2\x80\x9d.
