The stage of perfection is called trance, or sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi, when one\xc3\x95s mind is completely restrained from material mental activities by practice of yoga. This is \ncharacterized by one\xc3\x95s ability to see the self by the pure mind and to relish and rejoice in the self. In that joyous state, one is situated in boundless transcendental happiness and enjoys himself through transcendental senses. \nEstablished thus, one never departs from the truth, and upon gaining this he \nthinks there is no greater gain. Being situated in such a position, one is never shaken, even in the midst of greatest difficulty. This indeed is actual freedom from all miseries arising from material contact.
PURPORTBy practice of yoga one becomes gradually detached from material concepts. This is the primary characteristic of the yoga principle. And after this, one becomes situated in trance, or sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi which means that the yog\xe2\x80\x9d realizes the Supersoul through transcendental mind and intelligence, without any of the misgivings of identifying the self with the Superself. Yoga practice is more or less based on the principles of the Pata\xc5\x81jali system. Some unauthorized commentators try to identify the individual soul with the Supersoul, and the monists think this to be liberation, but they do not understand the real \npurpose of the Pata\xc5\x81jali system of yoga. There is an acceptance of '
b'transcendental pleasure in the Pata\xc5\x81jali system, but the monists do not accept this transcendental pleasure out of fear of jeopardizing the theory of oneness. The duality of knowledge and knower is not accepted by the nondualist, but in this verse transcendental pleasure\xc3\x91realized through transcendental senses\xc3\x91is accepted. And this is corroborated by the Pata\xc5\x81jali Muni, the famous exponent of the yoga system. The great sage declares in his citi-\xe2\x80\x9caktir iti.\nThis citi-\xe2\x80\x9cakti, or internal potency, is transcendental. Puru\xc5\x92\xe2\x88\x92rtha means material religiosity, economic development, sense gratification and, at the end, the attempt to become one with the Supreme. This "oneness with the Supreme" is called kaivalyam by the monist. But according to Pata\xc5\x81jali, this kaivalyam is an internal, or transcendental, potency by which the living entity becomes aware of his constitutional position. In the words of Lord Caitanya, this state of affairs is called ceto-darpa\xe2\x80\x9aa-m\xe2\x88\x92rjanam, or clearance of the impure \nmirror of the mind. This "clearance" is actually liberation, or bhava-mah\xe2\x88\x92d\xe2\x88\x92v\xe2\x88\x92gni-nirv\xe2\x88\x92pa\xe2\x80\x9aam. The theory of nirv\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa!also \npreliminary!corresponds with this principle. In the Bh\xe2\x88\x92gavatam this is called The Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 also confirms this situation in this verse.After nirv\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, or material cessation, there is the manifestation of spiritual activities, or devotional service of the Lord, known as K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness. In \nthe words of the this is the "real life of the living entity." M\xe2\x88\x92y\xe2\x88\x92, or illusion, is the condition of spiritual life contaminated by material infection. Liberation from this material infection does not mean destruction of the original eternal position of the living entity. Pata\xc5\x81jali also accepts this by his words This citi-\xe2\x80\x9cakti or transcendental pleasure, is real life. This is confirmed in the Ved\xe2\x88\x92nta-as \xe2\x88\x92nandamayo \xc3\x95bhy\xe2\x88\x92s\xe2\x88\x92t. This natural transcendental pleasure is the ultimate goal of yoga and is easily achieved by execution of devotional service, or bhakti-yoga. Bhaktiyoga will be vividly described in the Seventh Chapter of Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92.In the yoga system, as described in this chapter, there are two kinds of sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi, called sampraj\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92ta-sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi and asampraj\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92ta-sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi. When one becomes \nsituated in the transcendental position by various philosophical researches, it is called sampraj\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92ta-sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi. In the asampraj\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92ta-sam\xe2\x88\x92dhi there is no longer '
b'any connection with mundane pleasure, for one is then transcendental to all sorts of happiness derived from the senses. When the yog\xe2\x80\x9d is once situated in that transcendental position, he is never shaken from it. Unless the yog\xe2\x80\x9d is able to reach this position, he is unsuccessful. Today\xc3\x95s so-called yoga practice, which involves various sense pleasures, is contradictory. A yog\xe2\x80\x9d indulging in sex and intoxication is a mockery. Even those yog\xe2\x80\x9ds who are attracted by the \nsiddhis (perfections) in the process of yoga are not perfectly situated. If the yog\xe2\x80\x9ds are attracted by the by-products of yoga, then they cannot attain the \nstage of perfection, as is stated in this verse. Persons, therefore, indulging in the make-show practice of gymnastic feats or siddhis should know that the aim of yoga is lost in that way.The best practice of yoga in this age is K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness, which is not baffling. A K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa conscious person is so happy in his occupation that he does not aspire after any other happiness. There are many impediments, especially in this age of hypocrisy, to practicing ha\xc4\xb1ha-yoga, dhy\xe2\x88\x92na-yoga, and j\xc5\x81\xe2\x88\x92na-yoga, \nbut there is no such problem in executing karma-yoga or bhakti-yoga.As long as the material body exists, one has to meet the demands of the body, namely eating, sleeping, defending and mating. But a person who is in pure bhakti-yoga or in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness does not arouse the senses while meeting the demands of the body. Rather, he accepts the bare necessities of life, making the best use of a bad bargain, and enjoys transcendental happiness in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness. He is callous toward incidental occurrences!such as accidents, disease, scarcity and even the death of a most dear relative!but he is always alert to execute his duties in K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa consciousness or bhakti-yoga. Accidents never deviate him from his duty. As stated in the Bhagavad-g\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92, \xe2\x88\x92gam\xe2\x88\x92p\xe2\x88\x92yino \xc3\x95nity\xe2\x88\x92s t\xe2\x88\x92\xe2\x80\xb9s titik\xc5\x92asva bh\xe2\x88\x92rata. He endures all such incidental \noccurences because he knows that they come and go and do not affect his duties. In this way he achieves the highest perfection in yoga practice.
