PURPORTThe supreme abode of the Personality of Godhead, K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa, is described in the Brahma-sa\xe2\x80\xb9hit\xe2\x88\x92 as cint\xe2\x88\x92ma\xe2\x80\x9ai-dh\xe2\x88\x92ma, a place where all desires are fulfilled. The supreme abode of Lord K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa known as Goloka V\xe2\x80\x9end\xe2\x88\x92vana is full of palaces made of touchstone. There are also trees which are called \xc3\x92desire trees\xc3\x93 that supply any type of eatable upon demand, and there are cows known as surabhi cows which supply a limitless supply of milk. In this abode, the Lord is served by hundreds of thousands of goddesses of fortune (Lak\xc5\x92m\xe2\x80\x9ds), and He is \ncalled Govinda, the primal Lord and the cause of all causes. The Lord is accustomed to blow His flute (venum kvanantam). His transcendental form is the most attractive in all the worlds\xc3\x91His eyes are like the lotus petals and the color of His body like clouds. He is so attractive that His beauty excels that of thousands of cupids. He wears saffron cloth, a garland around His neck and a peacock feather in His hair. In the G\xe2\x80\x9dt\xe2\x88\x92 Lord Kr\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa gives only a small hint of His personal abode (Goloka V\xe2\x80\x9end\xe2\x88\x92vana) which is the supermost planet in the \nspiritual kingdom. A vivid description is given in the Brahma-sa\xe2\x80\xb9hit\xe2\x88\x92. Vedic literature states that there is nothing superior to the abode of the Supreme \nGodhead, and that that abode is the ultimate destination. When one attains to it, he never returns to the material world. K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa\xc3\x95s supreme abode and K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa Himself are nondifferent, being of the same quality. On this earth, V\xe2\x80\x9end\xe2\x88\x92vana, ninety miles southeast of Delhi, is a replica of that supreme Goloka V\xe2\x80\x9end\xe2\x88\x92vana located in the spiritual sky. When K\xe2\x80\x9e\xc5\x92\xe2\x80\x9aa descended